1. Estimate pairwise FST for all populations

We can convert to raw format

plink \
--keep-allele-order \
--bfile output/quality_control/file10 \
--recodeA \
--out output/fst/file1 \
--silent;
grep 'samples\|variants\|remaining' output/fst/file1.log
## 10157 variants loaded from .bim file.
## 10157 variants and 89 people pass filters and QC.

Look at https://rdrr.io/cran/StAMPP/man/stamppFst.html for details of Fst estimations

pop_pairwise <-
  read.PLINK(
    here(
      "output", "fst", "file1.raw"
    ),
    quiet = FALSE,
    chunkSize = 1000,
    parallel = require("parallel"),
    n.cores = 4
  )

summary(pop_pairwise)

Now lets convert the genlight object to Stampp format, and estimate pairwise Fst values

The command below would also work, but you can simplify it and put only the numbers: pop_pairwise2 <- stamppFst(pop_pairwise, nboots=10, percent=95 + nclusters=8)

This chunk will take a couple minutes to run.

# Convert
pop_pairwise2 <- stamppConvert(pop_pairwise, type="genlight")

# I am runing with 10 bootstraps, using 95% percentile to calculate confidence intervals, and 8 threads
pop_pairwise2 <- stamppFst(pop_pairwise2, 10, 95, 8)

Save it, so we do not have to run it again

saveRDS(
  pop_pairwise2, here(
    "output", "fst", "pop_pairwise2.rds"
  )
)

To load it

pop_pairwise2 <- readRDS(
  here(
    "output", "fst", "pop_pairwise2.rds"
  )
)

Now lets look at the object

summary(pop_pairwise2)
##            Length Class      Mode   
## Fsts       25     -none-     numeric
## Pvalues    25     -none-     numeric
## Bootstraps 16     data.frame list

If you want you can save the fst values as csv.

# Convert to data frame
pop_pairwise2_df <- data.frame(pop_pairwise2$Fsts)

# Save it
write.csv(pop_pairwise2_df, file = here("output", "fst", "pop_pairwise2_df.csv"))

We can subset the object

# Convert the Fsts component to a data frame
fst_df <- as.data.frame(pop_pairwise2$Fsts)

# Convert the Pvalues component to a data frame
pvalues_df <- as.data.frame(pop_pairwise2$Pvalues)

# For Bootstraps, since it's already a data frame-like structure, it can be converted directly
bootstraps_df <- as.data.frame(pop_pairwise2$Bootstraps)

All the p-values are zero, indicating statistical significance

Update names

# Original long names
long_names <- c("Background_Female_Dead", "Background_Male_Dead", "Selection_Female_Alive", "Selection_Male_Alive", "Background_Female_Alive")

# Create a mapping of long names to short names
name_mapping <- setNames(c("B_F_D", "B_M_D", "S_F_A", "S_M_A", "B_F_A"), long_names)

# Assuming 'fst_df' is your data frame containing Fst values
# Replace row names
rownames(fst_df) <- name_mapping[rownames(fst_df)]

# Replace column names
colnames(fst_df) <- name_mapping[colnames(fst_df)]

# Now 'fst_df' has the shorter names for plotting
print(fst_df)

Now lets plot the data with ggplot. You can click in the little square on the top left of the plot to open it on a new window. It will have the right proportions.

# Apply abs() to the 'value' column to get the absolute values
pairfst.long$value <- abs(pairfst.long$value)

pairfst.f <- ggplot(pairfst.long, aes(Var1, Var2)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = value), colour = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient(
    low = "white",
    high = "#71b6ff",
    name = "Fst",
    na.value = "white",
    limits = c(0, 0.05)
  ) +
  scale_x_discrete(position = "top") +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_text(aes(label = ifelse(
    is.na(value), "", formatC(value, digits = 4, format = "f")
  )), size = 6) +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 20),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    axis.text.y = element_text(hjust = 0, size = 20)
  )
pairfst.f

While the Fst between the wild populations, NEW and MAN, is 0.04, the values between them the the autogenous is 0.13.

output_path <- here("output", "fst", "figures", "pairwise_estimates.pdf")
ggsave(output_path, pairfst.f, height = 6, width = 6, dpi = 300)

We will compare NEW vs MAN, NEW vs AUT, MAN vs AUT, then we can plot the estimates using a facet plot and add a smooth line to see if there are genomic regions with high differenciation

First we need to create a vcf with Plink. We can use the original file since we will compare all populations.

Convert to vcf

plink2 \
--keep-allele-order \
--bfile output/quality_control/file10 \
--recode vcf-4.2 id-delim="." \
--out output/fst/malathion \
--silent;
grep 'samples\|variants\|remaining' output/fst/malathion.log

Now we create a list of mosquitoes for each population

# Define the VCF file path
VCF_FILE="output/fst/malathion.vcf"

# Extract the list of individuals
INDIVIDUALS=$(bcftools query -l $VCF_FILE)

# Filter and create files for each population
echo "$INDIVIDUALS" | grep 'Selection_Male_Alive' > output/fst/sma.txt
echo "$INDIVIDUALS" | grep 'Selection_Female_Alive' > output/fst/sfa.txt
echo "$INDIVIDUALS" | grep 'Background_Male_Dead' > output/fst/bmd.txt
echo "$INDIVIDUALS" | grep 'Background_Female_Dead' > output/fst/bfd.txt
echo "$INDIVIDUALS" | grep 'Background_Female_Alive' > output/fst/bfa.txt

Now we can estimate Fst between the populations using vcftools. We can use overlapping windows for finer resolution

Male (S) vs males (B)

# Since we are using the SNP chip data, we can use a window of 1Mb and 100kb steps
vcftools --vcf output/fst/malathion.vcf \
         --weir-fst-pop output/fst/sma.txt \
         --weir-fst-pop output/fst/bmd.txt \
         --fst-window-size 1000000 \
         --fst-window-step 100000 \
         --out output/fst/maleS_maleB

Now we plot

# Calculate the middle position
combined_data$mid_pos <- with(combined_data, (BIN_START + BIN_END) / 2)

# Reorder the levels of the comparison factor
combined_data$comparison <- fct_relevel(combined_data$comparison, "SexB", "SexS", "Males", "Females", "FemalesB", "FemalesSBA")

# Define a set of pastel colors for three chromosomes
pastel_colors <- c("#ebd99f", "#B3CDE3", "#ffafe4") 

# Create the facet plot
window_fst <-
  ggplot(combined_data,
         aes(
           x = mid_pos,
           y = WEIGHTED_FST,
           color = as.factor(CHROM)
         )) +
  geom_point(size = 0.1) +
  facet_grid(comparison ~ CHROM, scales = "free_x") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = label_number(scale = 1e-6, suffix = "Mb")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = pastel_colors) +
  # Smooth line for SexB
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "SexB"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "black"
  ) +
  # Smooth line for SexS in red
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "SexS"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "black"
  ) +
  # Smooth line for Males in red
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "Males"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "red"
  ) +
    # Smooth line for Females in red
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "Females"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "red"
  ) +
    # Smooth line for FemalesB in black
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "FemalesB"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "black"
  ) +
      # Smooth line for FemalesSBA in orange
  geom_smooth(
    data = subset(combined_data, comparison == "FemalesSBA"),
    aes(group = CHROM),
    se = FALSE,
    span = 0.3,
    color = "orange"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Position", y = "Weighted Fst", title = "") +
  theme(
    strip.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = .5),
    strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = .5),
    panel.spacing.x = unit(1.01, "lines"),
    legend.position = "none"
  )
